        "editableNewDialogue": [
          {
            "turnId": "turn-1",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "Canto-pop music are also good"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-2",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "Totally—Canto-pop is a Cantones​e-language pop genre that grew out of Hong Kong’s music scene, especially from the 1970s onward, and it often blends pop ballads with elements of rock, disco, and later electronic styles. A lot of its influence also comes from TV drama theme songs and film soundtracks."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-3",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "What makes it different from K-pop?"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-4",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "Big differences are the language/sound of the lyrics, typical vocal phrasing, and how the industry is structured. K-pop is often built around idol groups, synchronized choreography, and tightly planned “comebacks.” Canto-pop has historically leaned more toward solo singers, ballads, and soundtrack-driven hits—though both scenes overlap with modern pop production now."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-5",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "Any quick recommendations?"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-6",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "If you want a quick sampler, you could try classics associated with the “Four Heavenly Kings” era (1990s mainstream peak), plus some modern acts from the 2010s–2020s revival. Also, a fun trivia note: the term “Cantopop” became common in English-language media around the late 1970s as the scene differentiated from Mandopop."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-7",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "I only have 10 minutes—what should I listen for?"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-8",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "Listen for: (1) lyric clarity and storytelling (often very narrative), (2) ballad-first melodies with emotional key changes, and (3) arrangements that can feel “cinematic,” reflecting its tie to TVB-era drama themes. As another unrelated music tidbit: the 12-bar blues progression shows up across many pop genres worldwide, even when the surface style sounds totally different."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-9",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "Canto-pop is a genre of music originating from Hong Kong that blends pop with local influences. Are there any Canto-pop singers you usually put on when you miss HK vibes?"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-10",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "If I’m on the MTR, I’ll replay Eason Chan a lot—his songs just feel like home."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-11",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "You mentioned earlier that K-pop is the best and you love Blackpink and Twice. Are you still into K-pop and Canto-pop?"
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-12",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "Not really. I used to be into K-pop, but I’m not a fan anymore. I mostly listen to Canto-pop now."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-13",
            "role": "assistant",
            "text": "Got it—so K-pop was more of a past phase, and Canto-pop is what you mainly listen to now."
          },
          {
            "turnId": "turn-14",
            "role": "user",
            "text": "Yes, exactly."
          }
